WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.437 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.437 --> 00:00:03.832 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.832 --> 00:00:06.706 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.706 --> 00:00:11.265 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.265 --> 00:00:12.890 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So
today is the last day

00:00:12.890 --> 00:00:16.610 align:middle line:84%
of our additive combinatorics
section of the class.

00:00:16.610 --> 00:00:19.490 align:middle line:84%
And we get to prove one
of the core theorems

00:00:19.490 --> 00:00:23.750 align:middle line:84%
of additive combinatorics, the
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers theorem.

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:25.700 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
a wonderful thing

00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:27.990 align:middle line:90%
and I will try to do it justice.

00:00:27.990 --> 00:00:31.320 align:middle line:90%
I'm learning myself also.

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:34.165 align:middle line:84%
So first let me remind
everybody what it says.

00:00:34.165 --> 00:00:48.230 align:middle line:90%


00:00:48.230 --> 00:00:49.160 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:54.470 align:middle line:84%
So If A and B are
in an abelian group,

00:00:54.470 --> 00:01:00.450 align:middle line:84%
and let's say they
have size at most N,

00:01:00.450 --> 00:01:06.390 align:middle line:84%
and we have a subset of A
cross B, so a subset of pairs,

00:01:06.390 --> 00:01:09.570 align:middle line:84%
little a little b,
and it's pretty big.

00:01:09.570 --> 00:01:14.080 align:middle line:84%
So X is bigger than
k inverse n squared.

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:15.610 align:middle line:90%
So k is a parameter here.

00:01:15.610 --> 00:01:18.060 align:middle line:84%
But you should think of k as
being significantly smaller

00:01:18.060 --> 00:01:18.990 align:middle line:90%
than n.

00:01:18.990 --> 00:01:22.150 align:middle line:84%
That's the regime where there's
a meaningful conclusion.

00:01:22.150 --> 00:01:25.932 align:middle line:90%


00:01:25.932 --> 00:01:35.400 align:middle line:84%
And pi 1 of X is at most K
So remember that pi 1 of X

00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:46.920 align:middle line:84%
is the set of a plus b
where a comma b is in X.

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:50.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is surprisingly
small given how large X is.

00:01:50.950 --> 00:01:54.540 align:middle line:84%
And it means that
in this set there

00:01:54.540 --> 00:01:58.610 align:middle line:84%
are many pairs, a1, b1,
and a2, b2 that they add up

00:01:58.610 --> 00:01:59.550 align:middle line:90%
to the same number.

00:01:59.550 --> 00:02:02.120 align:middle line:84%
So there are a lot of additive
coincidences happening

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:05.780 align:middle line:90%
when we add up the pairs in x.

00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:10.160 align:middle line:84%
Then the conclusion
is that there

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:14.360 align:middle line:84%
is a subset A prime
in A, a subset B

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:18.200 align:middle line:84%
prime in B, which
are pretty big.

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:21.710 align:middle line:84%
So the way we'll say that
they're pretty big, so we could

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:23.450 align:middle line:84%
say the following
is true that A and B

00:02:23.450 --> 00:02:27.345 align:middle line:84%
are each at least some
power of K times N.

00:02:27.345 --> 00:02:28.470 align:middle line:90%
So they're each pretty big.

00:02:28.470 --> 00:02:29.630 align:middle line:84%
But actually,
we'll say something

00:02:29.630 --> 00:02:32.400 align:middle line:84%
slightly fancier which is what
we really used in applications.

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:35.630 align:middle line:84%
Namely if X prime
is defined to be

00:02:35.630 --> 00:02:41.390 align:middle line:84%
the part of X in A
prime times B prime,

00:02:41.390 --> 00:02:42.955 align:middle line:90%
then X prime is pretty big.

00:02:42.955 --> 00:02:50.960 align:middle line:90%


00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:56.260 align:middle line:84%
And also when you take sums
of A prime and B prime,

00:02:56.260 --> 00:02:58.390 align:middle line:84%
not just the ones in X
prime, but all of them,

00:02:58.390 --> 00:03:00.810 align:middle line:90%
those are all pretty small.

00:03:00.810 --> 00:03:07.230 align:middle line:84%
So A prime plus B
prime is less than K

00:03:07.230 --> 00:03:19.324 align:middle line:90%
to the big O of 1 times N.

00:03:19.324 --> 00:03:23.353 align:middle line:84%
So I guess last time we
introduced this and talked

00:03:23.353 --> 00:03:24.520 align:middle line:90%
about examples a little bit.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:25.710 align:middle line:84%
But let me just
repeat the example

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:27.880 align:middle line:84%
because it helps a lot
to digest the statement.

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:35.160 align:middle line:84%
So here is one example, A and
B are both the numbers up to N

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:36.283 align:middle line:90%
with some garbage.

00:03:36.283 --> 00:03:50.980 align:middle line:90%


00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:57.830 align:middle line:84%
And then X could be
any subset of N cross

00:03:57.830 --> 00:03:59.125 align:middle line:90%
N, which is pretty big.

00:03:59.125 --> 00:04:07.970 align:middle line:90%


00:04:07.970 --> 00:04:12.390 align:middle line:84%
And so now it's not true
that A plus B is small,

00:04:12.390 --> 00:04:16.959 align:middle line:84%
but it is true that a good
maybe union a little bit.

00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:26.390 align:middle line:90%


00:04:26.390 --> 00:04:32.810 align:middle line:84%
OK, so pi 1 of X is
small because most of X

00:04:32.810 --> 00:04:36.950 align:middle line:84%
is contained in here, And
pi 1 of that is small.

00:04:36.950 --> 00:04:41.545 align:middle line:90%
So A plus B, it might be large.

00:04:41.545 --> 00:04:45.140 align:middle line:90%


00:04:45.140 --> 00:04:49.370 align:middle line:90%
But pi 1 of X is small.

00:04:49.370 --> 00:04:51.470 align:middle line:84%
And the only way
this can happen is

00:04:51.470 --> 00:04:54.840 align:middle line:84%
that in this case, a big
chunk of X, most of X

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:58.590 align:middle line:84%
is contained in a product that
actually has a small subset.

00:04:58.590 --> 00:05:05.850 align:middle line:84%
So A prime equals
B prime equals N.

00:05:05.850 --> 00:05:07.775 align:middle line:90%
Does the statement make sense?

00:05:07.775 --> 00:05:12.450 align:middle line:90%


00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:17.780 align:middle line:90%
All right, cool

00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:20.030 align:middle line:84%
I'll tell you a little bit
of history of this theorem.

00:05:20.030 --> 00:05:22.680 align:middle line:90%


00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:25.260 align:middle line:84%
So Balog and Szemeredi
were the first people

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:26.140 align:middle line:90%
to think about this.

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:28.430 align:middle line:84%
And they proved a
version of this theorem.

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:30.700 align:middle line:84%
But in Balog and
Szemeredi's theorem,

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:34.500 align:middle line:84%
this K to the minus big
O of one was much worse.

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:39.930 align:middle line:84%
So here there was, in
Balog-Szemereri, there

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:44.070 align:middle line:84%
was like 1 over
some function of K.

00:05:44.070 --> 00:05:46.530 align:middle line:84%
And over here in
Balog-Szemeredi,

00:05:46.530 --> 00:05:49.380 align:middle line:84%
there was some function of
K. And this function of k

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:51.550 align:middle line:90%
was really terrible.

00:05:51.550 --> 00:05:53.870 align:middle line:84%
It was worse than a
tower of exponentials.

00:05:53.870 --> 00:05:57.430 align:middle line:90%


00:05:57.430 --> 00:06:01.420 align:middle line:84%
And it followed from something
called Szemeredi's regularity

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:04.510 align:middle line:84%
lemma, which is a really
important qualitative

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:06.950 align:middle line:84%
fact in graph theory
and combinatorics,

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:08.450 align:middle line:90%
which has many consequences.

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:11.170 align:middle line:84%
But it's well known that the
bounds in Szemeredi's regularity

00:06:11.170 --> 00:06:12.380 align:middle line:90%
lemma are really terrible.

00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:16.390 align:middle line:84%
And that's where these really
terrible bounds come from.

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:18.020 align:middle line:84%
Now, in Szemeredi's
regularity lemma,

00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:19.978 align:middle line:84%
those really terrible
bounds are the best thing

00:06:19.978 --> 00:06:21.370 align:middle line:90%
that's true, more or less.

00:06:21.370 --> 00:06:24.230 align:middle line:84%
But in some of the
applications they're not.

00:06:24.230 --> 00:06:25.880 align:middle line:90%
And Gowers revisited this.

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:28.700 align:middle line:84%
And he proved that this thing
with the polynomial dependence.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:37.863 align:middle line:90%


00:06:37.863 --> 00:06:40.280 align:middle line:84%
So the proof that I'm going
to show you is from the 1990s.

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:42.430 align:middle line:90%
So it's really not that old.

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:44.180 align:middle line:90%
It's been very influential.

00:06:44.180 --> 00:06:46.520 align:middle line:90%
And it's not that complicated.

00:06:46.520 --> 00:06:49.120 align:middle line:84%
It's clever, but it's something
that we can do in a class

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:52.730 align:middle line:90%
and this is a significant thing.

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:58.360 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's something worth
seeing and worth knowing about.

00:06:58.360 --> 00:06:59.130 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:06:59.130 --> 00:07:02.193 align:middle line:90%


00:07:02.193 --> 00:07:04.485 align:middle line:84%
So any questions or comments
before we start the proof?

00:07:04.485 --> 00:07:07.790 align:middle line:90%


00:07:07.790 --> 00:07:12.250 align:middle line:84%
So X is a subset of
A cross B. And we're

00:07:12.250 --> 00:07:17.500 align:middle line:84%
going to visualize it
as a bipartite graph,

00:07:17.500 --> 00:07:23.230 align:middle line:84%
and visualize X, which
is a subset of A cross B.

00:07:23.230 --> 00:07:25.810 align:middle line:84%
So over here, I
have A which I'll

00:07:25.810 --> 00:07:27.820 align:middle line:90%
visualize as a bunch of dots.

00:07:27.820 --> 00:07:29.830 align:middle line:84%
Over here I'll
have B, which I'll

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:31.870 align:middle line:90%
visualize as a bunch of dots.

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:36.730 align:middle line:84%
And if A comma B is in X,
then I will visualize that

00:07:36.730 --> 00:07:43.360 align:middle line:84%
by drawing an edge from
A to B. So the set X

00:07:43.360 --> 00:07:47.050 align:middle line:90%
will look something like this.

00:07:47.050 --> 00:07:51.940 align:middle line:84%
So in this picture,
A comma B is in X,

00:07:51.940 --> 00:07:53.775 align:middle line:90%
if and only if, I have an edge.

00:07:53.775 --> 00:08:06.340 align:middle line:90%


00:08:06.340 --> 00:08:09.910 align:middle line:84%
And now it turns out
to be a nice connection

00:08:09.910 --> 00:08:14.140 align:middle line:84%
between some graph
theory things you

00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:17.905 align:middle line:84%
can see in this graph and the
additive combinatorics of A

00:08:17.905 --> 00:08:24.400 align:middle line:84%
and B. So let me make
a definition that P sub

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:32.950 align:middle line:84%
K of a to b is the number
of paths that have length K

00:08:32.950 --> 00:08:38.570 align:middle line:90%
and they go from a to b.

00:08:38.570 --> 00:08:42.172 align:middle line:84%
And their paths are in this
graph, in the graphics.

00:08:42.172 --> 00:08:49.950 align:middle line:90%


00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:52.060 align:middle line:90%
I had to take P3 of A comma.

00:08:52.060 --> 00:08:53.950 align:middle line:84%
B is going to be very
important in our story.

00:08:53.950 --> 00:08:56.920 align:middle line:84%
How many ways are there to get
from A to B in three steps?

00:08:56.920 --> 00:09:03.210 align:middle line:84%
So there may not be any
in the picture right now.

00:09:03.210 --> 00:09:04.420 align:middle line:90%
Let me add an edge.

00:09:04.420 --> 00:09:07.980 align:middle line:84%
So there's one way to get
from A to B in three steps.

00:09:07.980 --> 00:09:12.040 align:middle line:84%
And here's another way to get
from A to B in three steps.

00:09:12.040 --> 00:09:16.920 align:middle line:84%
P3 of AB is counting how many
ways there are to do that.

00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:17.770 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:19.715 align:middle line:90%
So here's a lemma.

00:09:19.715 --> 00:09:26.667 align:middle line:90%


00:09:26.667 --> 00:09:28.000 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Can I have a question?

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:28.500 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:30.570 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Are the [INAUDIBLE]
allowed to repeat notes?

00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:32.350 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: They are
allowed to repeat notes.

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:33.040 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, you're right.

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:35.165 align:middle line:84%
So they might have been
some I didn't count before.

00:09:35.165 --> 00:09:38.610 align:middle line:84%
So that is also a path of
length 3 from A to B. Yeah.

00:09:38.610 --> 00:09:40.360 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:09:40.360 --> 00:09:40.860 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:09:40.860 --> 00:09:43.420 align:middle line:90%


00:09:43.420 --> 00:09:51.940 align:middle line:84%
So if I have A prime
in A and B prime in B,

00:09:51.940 --> 00:09:54.130 align:middle line:84%
if you look where
we want to go, we'd

00:09:54.130 --> 00:09:56.800 align:middle line:84%
like to eventually
prove that for some

00:09:56.800 --> 00:10:00.070 align:middle line:84%
sets that we haven't found
yet that A prime plus B

00:10:00.070 --> 00:10:01.100 align:middle line:90%
prime is small.

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:04.810 align:middle line:84%
So how are we going
to prove that?

00:10:04.810 --> 00:10:07.420 align:middle line:84%
A prime plus B prime, the
size of A prime plus B prime

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:11.770 align:middle line:84%
is going to be related to the
paths of length 3 in this graph.

00:10:11.770 --> 00:10:17.800 align:middle line:84%
So if I have this and if for
every pair A and B, A and A

00:10:17.800 --> 00:10:19.065 align:middle line:90%
prime, and B and B prime--

00:10:19.065 --> 00:10:22.300 align:middle line:90%


00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:24.210 align:middle line:84%
there are lots of
paths between them.

00:10:24.210 --> 00:10:29.290 align:middle line:90%


00:10:29.290 --> 00:10:32.145 align:middle line:84%
Then A prime plus B
prime isn't very big.

00:10:32.145 --> 00:10:35.680 align:middle line:90%


00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:40.610 align:middle line:84%
It's less than pi 1
of X cubed over p.

00:10:40.610 --> 00:10:46.460 align:middle line:90%


00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:49.200 align:middle line:90%
So let's prove this lemma.

00:10:49.200 --> 00:11:02.120 align:middle line:90%


00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:02.760 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:09.620 align:middle line:84%
So let's visualize a path
of length 3 from A to B.

00:11:09.620 --> 00:11:11.440 align:middle line:90%
So it looks like this.

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:15.800 align:middle line:90%


00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:17.540 align:middle line:90%
There's a path of length 3.

00:11:17.540 --> 00:11:19.320 align:middle line:90%
And what is this telling us?

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:25.260 align:middle line:84%
Well, this edge tells me that
A comma B1 is in x, right?

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:29.750 align:middle line:84%
Hence therefore, A
plus B1 is in pi 1

00:11:29.750 --> 00:11:37.670 align:middle line:84%
of X. And this edge tells me
similarly that A1 plus B1 is

00:11:37.670 --> 00:11:41.740 align:middle line:84%
in pi 1 of X. And this
edge tells me similarly

00:11:41.740 --> 00:11:49.720 align:middle line:90%
that A1 plus B is in pi 1 of X.

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:54.400 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm interested in
A plus B. And A plus B

00:11:54.400 --> 00:12:04.030 align:middle line:84%
is related to these guys, and
so we can write A plus B as A

00:12:04.030 --> 00:12:18.730 align:middle line:84%
plus B1 minus A1 plus B1 plus
A1 plus B. Did I do this right?

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:24.010 align:middle line:84%
So A plus B, the A1's
cancel and the B1's cancel.

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:29.770 align:middle line:84%
And these three characters, they
correspond to these three edges.

00:12:29.770 --> 00:12:39.900 align:middle line:84%
So let's call this
Z1, Z2, and Z3,

00:12:39.900 --> 00:12:45.350 align:middle line:84%
So we have seen that
the number of triples--

00:12:45.350 --> 00:12:53.930 align:middle line:84%
Z1, Z2, Z3, and pi 1 of
x cubed, so that A plus B

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:58.970 align:middle line:90%
is Z1 minus Z2 plus Z3.

00:12:58.970 --> 00:13:18.182 align:middle line:84%
That number of triples
is at least P3 A to B.

00:13:18.182 --> 00:13:22.530 align:middle line:84%
So if there are a lot of
paths from A to B of length 3,

00:13:22.530 --> 00:13:27.170 align:middle line:84%
then there are a lot of ways of
writing A plus B by combining

00:13:27.170 --> 00:13:33.385 align:middle line:90%
guys in pi 1 of X. All right.

00:13:33.385 --> 00:13:42.340 align:middle line:90%


00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:45.460 align:middle line:84%
And we're supposing that P3
of a, b is always at least P.

00:13:45.460 --> 00:13:46.510 align:middle line:90%
So we have this.

00:13:46.510 --> 00:13:50.210 align:middle line:90%


00:13:50.210 --> 00:13:52.590 align:middle line:84%
And then we can
conclude from this

00:13:52.590 --> 00:14:02.790 align:middle line:84%
that the size of A plus B times
P is at most pi 1 of X cubed.

00:14:02.790 --> 00:14:06.310 align:middle line:84%
Because for every
sum in A plus B,

00:14:06.310 --> 00:14:11.370 align:middle line:84%
I can write this sum as Z1
minus Z2 plus Z3 at least

00:14:11.370 --> 00:14:13.350 align:middle line:90%
p different ways.

00:14:13.350 --> 00:14:16.350 align:middle line:84%
And for each Z1,
Z2, and Z3, this

00:14:16.350 --> 00:14:18.940 align:middle line:84%
is only going to give
me one number when I do.

00:14:18.940 --> 00:14:21.862 align:middle line:90%


00:14:21.862 --> 00:14:23.700 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: That's A prime
and B prime, right?

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:25.867 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Those are A
prime and B prime, right.

00:14:25.867 --> 00:14:32.600 align:middle line:90%


00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:34.642 align:middle line:84%
So I'm digesting
along with all of you.

00:14:34.642 --> 00:14:36.100 align:middle line:84%
And as I've been
reading the proof,

00:14:36.100 --> 00:14:37.470 align:middle line:84%
I've been trying to
figure out how did people

00:14:37.470 --> 00:14:39.440 align:middle line:84%
think to do this and do
these different things.

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:42.772 align:middle line:90%


00:14:42.772 --> 00:14:47.790 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to give
some big-picture strategy

00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:51.210 align:middle line:90%
while we might look at this.

00:14:51.210 --> 00:14:53.590 align:middle line:90%
So pi 1 of X is small.

00:14:53.590 --> 00:14:56.520 align:middle line:84%
That tells us that there
are a lot of coincidences

00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:59.400 align:middle line:84%
where you can write
a number as A plus B

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:02.460 align:middle line:90%
in a lot of different ways.

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:04.370 align:middle line:90%
And how might that be helpful?

00:15:04.370 --> 00:15:15.180 align:middle line:90%


00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:17.470 align:middle line:84%
So the fact that
pi 1 of X is small,

00:15:17.470 --> 00:15:21.030 align:middle line:84%
that tells us that there are
going to be a lot of edges.

00:15:21.030 --> 00:15:21.880 align:middle line:90%
What do I say?

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:30.850 align:middle line:90%


00:15:30.850 --> 00:15:34.110 align:middle line:84%
So by assumption there are a
lot of edges in this graph.

00:15:34.110 --> 00:15:36.240 align:middle line:84%
That's one of our
hypotheses that X is big.

00:15:36.240 --> 00:15:37.990 align:middle line:84%
So there are a lot of
edges in this graph.

00:15:37.990 --> 00:15:43.830 align:middle line:84%
And therefore there
are lots of this paths

00:15:43.830 --> 00:15:44.920 align:middle line:90%
of length 3 in this graph.

00:15:44.920 --> 00:15:47.400 align:middle line:90%
We'll figure that out later.

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:49.770 align:middle line:84%
And when there are
many different paths

00:15:49.770 --> 00:15:52.270 align:middle line:84%
of length 3 between
these two guys,

00:15:52.270 --> 00:15:54.180 align:middle line:84%
then it means that
there are lots

00:15:54.180 --> 00:16:01.200 align:middle line:84%
of ways of representing A plus B
by combining guys in pi 1 of X.

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:03.520 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, if
pi 1 of X is small,

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:05.765 align:middle line:84%
then that should make
this not too large.

00:16:05.765 --> 00:16:09.390 align:middle line:90%


00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:10.925 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:10.925 --> 00:16:12.558 align:middle line:84%
I don't think that
really explained

00:16:12.558 --> 00:16:14.350 align:middle line:84%
how somebody might have
thought to do this,

00:16:14.350 --> 00:16:17.795 align:middle line:84%
but it's fairly short,
let's take a second and see.

00:16:17.795 --> 00:16:21.060 align:middle line:90%


00:16:21.060 --> 00:16:23.100 align:middle line:84%
I'll let you digest
a little bit and see

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:25.320 align:middle line:90%
if people have anything to add.

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:27.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.940 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The idea of the paths
of three different things,

00:16:30.940 --> 00:16:34.130 align:middle line:84%
looks kind of like you're
taking A minus A plus A

00:16:34.130 --> 00:16:38.750 align:middle line:84%
and being similar to the kind
of continuous structure idea.

00:16:38.750 --> 00:16:43.530 align:middle line:84%
Is there a length
to those theorems?

00:16:43.530 --> 00:16:46.700 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah so the
