00:16:46.700 --> 00:16:49.610 align:middle line:84%
bit like [? plunica ?]
and is there a link

00:16:49.610 --> 00:16:53.300 align:middle line:90%
to the [? plunicane ?] equality.

00:16:53.300 --> 00:16:58.978 align:middle line:90%
Maybe Yeah?

00:16:58.978 --> 00:17:01.520 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is there something
special about paths of length 3?

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:05.522 align:middle line:84%
It seems like this should work
for any odd number of paths.

00:17:05.522 --> 00:17:06.480 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah OK.

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:09.000 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, why did
we pick paths of length three.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.990 align:middle line:84%
There's really nothing special
about paths of length 3.

00:17:11.990 --> 00:17:16.130 align:middle line:84%
It would be some similar
estimate for any length.

00:17:16.130 --> 00:17:20.527 align:middle line:84%
And 3 is the length where the
later part of the proof, we

00:17:20.527 --> 00:17:21.610 align:middle line:90%
managed to get it to work.

00:17:21.610 --> 00:17:29.740 align:middle line:90%


00:17:29.740 --> 00:17:30.240 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:33.000 align:middle line:90%


00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:37.180 align:middle line:84%
So next, let's think a
bit about how many edges

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:39.180 align:middle line:84%
there are in this graph
and how many paths there

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:41.640 align:middle line:84%
are of length 2, and how many
paths there are of length 3,

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:43.860 align:middle line:90%
and stuff.

00:17:43.860 --> 00:17:48.090 align:middle line:84%
Let's just orient
ourselves to this graph.

00:17:48.090 --> 00:18:03.240 align:middle line:84%
So OK, I'll call this some basic
estimates and PK, PK of AB.

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:04.770 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let me
frame it this way.

00:18:04.770 --> 00:18:07.210 align:middle line:84%
Let me state a lemma
about paths of length 3.

00:18:07.210 --> 00:18:09.820 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll start to
do some things about that.

00:18:09.820 --> 00:18:12.180 align:middle line:84%
So to finish the proof of
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers,

00:18:12.180 --> 00:18:13.920 align:middle line:90%
there's a key lemma.

00:18:13.920 --> 00:18:17.460 align:middle line:84%
And it's just a lemma
in graph theory.

00:18:17.460 --> 00:18:20.820 align:middle line:84%
So all of the additive
structure went

00:18:20.820 --> 00:18:24.600 align:middle line:84%
into writing this and
noticing that things cancel.

00:18:24.600 --> 00:18:26.220 align:middle line:84%
And now we have our
graph theory lemma

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:28.600 align:middle line:84%
about paths of
length 3 in a graph.

00:18:28.600 --> 00:18:32.990 align:middle line:84%
So the main lemma
says that if X is in.

00:18:32.990 --> 00:18:38.290 align:middle line:84%
A cross B that X is bigger
than K inverse times the size

00:18:38.290 --> 00:18:41.920 align:middle line:90%
of A times the size of B.

00:18:41.920 --> 00:18:47.220 align:middle line:84%
Then there are big sets with
lots of paths between them.

00:18:47.220 --> 00:18:50.290 align:middle line:90%


00:18:50.290 --> 00:18:55.840 align:middle line:84%
So then there exists A
prime in A and B prime

00:18:55.840 --> 00:19:02.860 align:middle line:84%
in B so that if
we define X prime

00:19:02.860 --> 00:19:06.310 align:middle line:84%
is the part of X in A
prime cross B prime,

00:19:06.310 --> 00:19:08.040 align:middle line:90%
then X prime is pretty big.

00:19:08.040 --> 00:19:15.850 align:middle line:90%


00:19:15.850 --> 00:19:22.390 align:middle line:84%
And for every A and
A prime and B and B

00:19:22.390 --> 00:19:30.390 align:middle line:84%
prime the number of length 3
paths from A to B is at least K

00:19:30.390 --> 00:19:39.520 align:middle line:90%
to the minus O of 1 A B.

00:19:39.520 --> 00:19:42.327 align:middle line:84%
So if you combine this
lemma and this key lemma,

00:19:42.327 --> 00:19:44.910 align:middle line:84%
and just put them together, you
get the Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers

00:19:44.910 --> 00:19:46.020 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:19:46.020 --> 00:19:49.560 align:middle line:84%
And the reason
that 3 appears here

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:53.315 align:middle line:84%
is it's the smallest number
where this key lemma is true.

00:19:53.315 --> 00:20:01.020 align:middle line:90%


00:20:01.020 --> 00:20:07.560 align:middle line:84%
So I'll let you in your mind
just fill in this is our P,

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:12.703 align:middle line:84%
and fill it in for P over here,
and you do a little algebra,

00:20:12.703 --> 00:20:14.620 align:middle line:84%
and that's the
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers theorem.

00:20:14.620 --> 00:20:35.780 align:middle line:90%


00:20:35.780 --> 00:20:37.450 align:middle line:84%
So if it's OK with
everybody, I'm

00:20:37.450 --> 00:20:39.470 align:middle line:84%
going to erase this and
the rest of the class,

00:20:39.470 --> 00:20:42.143 align:middle line:84%
we just focus on proving
this lemma from graph theory,

00:20:42.143 --> 00:20:43.560 align:middle line:84%
with the rest of
the proof of BSG.

00:20:43.560 --> 00:20:59.200 align:middle line:90%


00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:04.328 align:middle line:84%
So let's orient ourselves a
little bit about how many paths

00:21:04.328 --> 00:21:06.370 align:middle line:84%
there are in this graph
between different points,

00:21:06.370 --> 00:21:08.380 align:middle line:84%
and prove some
simple things first

00:21:08.380 --> 00:21:11.530 align:middle line:90%
before we prove this lemma.

00:21:11.530 --> 00:21:21.568 align:middle line:84%
So I'll call this a simple
bounds about PK a, b.

00:21:21.568 --> 00:21:33.350 align:middle line:90%


00:21:33.350 --> 00:21:33.850 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:21:33.850 --> 00:21:36.510 align:middle line:84%
So first let's think
about how many edges

00:21:36.510 --> 00:21:38.340 align:middle line:90%
there are in this graph.

00:21:38.340 --> 00:21:43.500 align:middle line:84%
So the number of
edges is the size

00:21:43.500 --> 00:21:50.730 align:middle line:84%
of X, which is at
least K inverse A B.

00:21:50.730 --> 00:21:53.490 align:middle line:84%
And then let's think
about how many paths there

00:21:53.490 --> 00:21:54.670 align:middle line:90%
are of different lengths.

00:21:54.670 --> 00:21:57.960 align:middle line:84%
So if I write PK
without an A or B,

00:21:57.960 --> 00:22:03.120 align:middle line:84%
this is the number
of paths of length K,

00:22:03.120 --> 00:22:05.290 align:middle line:84%
and they could start
or end anywhere.

00:22:05.290 --> 00:22:07.350 align:middle line:84%
But I will just
make the restriction

00:22:07.350 --> 00:22:09.330 align:middle line:84%
that they start
in A. It turns out

00:22:09.330 --> 00:22:12.180 align:middle line:84%
it's in a bipartite
graph It's simpler

00:22:12.180 --> 00:22:15.600 align:middle line:90%
to count things like this.

00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:21.260 align:middle line:84%
So P1 is just the number
of edges in the graph,

00:22:21.260 --> 00:22:23.510 align:middle line:84%
paths of length 1 are
just individual edges.

00:22:23.510 --> 00:22:35.500 align:middle line:84%
So this is the size of X, which
is at least K inverse A B. Now

00:22:35.500 --> 00:22:45.110 align:middle line:84%
a helpful thing to talk about is
the neighborhood of any vertex.

00:22:45.110 --> 00:22:48.295 align:middle line:84%
So if I have a
vertex A over here.

00:22:48.295 --> 00:22:52.250 align:middle line:84%
This is A and this is B.
I have vertex A over here.

00:22:52.250 --> 00:22:54.880 align:middle line:84%
There are some edges
coming out of it.

00:22:54.880 --> 00:22:59.920 align:middle line:84%
And this set here is called
the neighborhood of A.

00:22:59.920 --> 00:23:02.260 align:middle line:84%
And you can do it in the
other directions also.

00:23:02.260 --> 00:23:03.220 align:middle line:84%
It's the neighborhood
of A. Yeah?

00:23:03.220 --> 00:23:04.690 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: There's two
different K's up here, right?

00:23:04.690 --> 00:23:06.470 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: There
are two different K's.

00:23:06.470 --> 00:23:07.845 align:middle line:84%
Yeah there are
two different K's.

00:23:07.845 --> 00:23:09.520 align:middle line:90%
I apologize.

00:23:09.520 --> 00:23:10.060 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:11.140 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:11.140 --> 00:23:11.820 align:middle line:90%
Let's do this.

00:23:11.820 --> 00:23:24.917 align:middle line:90%


00:23:24.917 --> 00:23:31.500 align:middle line:90%
So P2, so that's the size of P1.

00:23:31.500 --> 00:23:40.400 align:middle line:84%
And then if I were to take
the average A and A of P1 of A

00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:46.100 align:middle line:84%
to anywhere, that would be
P1 divided by the size of A.

00:23:46.100 --> 00:23:50.840 align:middle line:84%
And so that would be at least
K inverse times the size of P.

00:23:50.840 --> 00:23:53.780 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
average degree of one

00:23:53.780 --> 00:23:55.710 align:middle line:90%
of these vertices on the left.

00:23:55.710 --> 00:23:58.430 align:middle line:84%
And it's at least
a decent fraction

00:23:58.430 --> 00:24:01.730 align:middle line:84%
of all the vertices
on the right.

00:24:01.730 --> 00:24:02.550 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:24:02.550 --> 00:24:05.900 align:middle line:84%
Now let's think about
paths of length 2.

00:24:05.900 --> 00:24:12.850 align:middle line:84%
So P2, a path of length
2 looks like this.

00:24:12.850 --> 00:24:18.430 align:middle line:90%


00:24:18.430 --> 00:24:21.100 align:middle line:84%
So there's some guy B
that it goes through here,

00:24:21.100 --> 00:24:23.590 align:middle line:84%
and then there
has to be somebody

00:24:23.590 --> 00:24:25.870 align:middle line:84%
who goes to B and
somebody who comes from B.

00:24:25.870 --> 00:24:29.560 align:middle line:84%
So this is the sum over b
of the size of neighborhood

00:24:29.560 --> 00:24:30.300 align:middle line:90%
of b squared.

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:35.020 align:middle line:90%


00:24:35.020 --> 00:24:37.480 align:middle line:84%
Well, if I just
were to take the sum

00:24:37.480 --> 00:24:39.440 align:middle line:84%
over b of the size
of neighborhood of b,

00:24:39.440 --> 00:24:41.380 align:middle line:90%
that would count the edges.

00:24:41.380 --> 00:24:44.140 align:middle line:84%
So whenever I'm interested in
the sum of somebody squared

00:24:44.140 --> 00:24:46.370 align:middle line:84%
and I have a nice formula
for the sum of somebody,

00:24:46.370 --> 00:24:49.690 align:middle line:84%
then it makes sense to
apply Cauchy-Schwarz.

00:24:49.690 --> 00:24:51.710 align:middle line:84%
So if you apply
Cauchy-Schwarz here,

00:24:51.710 --> 00:24:56.560 align:middle line:84%
you get the sum of N
of b quantity squared

00:24:56.560 --> 00:24:59.770 align:middle line:90%
over the size of b.

00:24:59.770 --> 00:25:05.380 align:middle line:84%
So that's at least K inverse
size of A size of B bar

00:25:05.380 --> 00:25:11.080 align:middle line:84%
all squared over the size of
B. And that works out to k

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:18.900 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 2 A squared B.

00:25:18.900 --> 00:25:20.640 align:middle line:90%
Now that kind of makes sense.

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:23.270 align:middle line:84%
So for reference, if we had
the complete graph with all

00:25:23.270 --> 00:25:25.670 align:middle line:84%
the edges, the number
of paths of length 2

00:25:25.670 --> 00:25:27.950 align:middle line:84%
would be A squared B.
You pick somebody in A,

00:25:27.950 --> 00:25:30.650 align:middle line:84%
you pick somebody in B,
you pick somebody in A.

00:25:30.650 --> 00:25:33.860 align:middle line:84%
And so this says that the
fraction of them is at least K

00:25:33.860 --> 00:25:36.080 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 2.

00:25:36.080 --> 00:25:38.360 align:middle line:84%
And that makes sense because
the fraction of edges

00:25:38.360 --> 00:25:39.750 align:middle line:90%
is K to the minus 1.

00:25:39.750 --> 00:25:43.010 align:middle line:84%
And we want two different
edges to both be in our path.

00:25:43.010 --> 00:25:46.970 align:middle line:84%
So that makes K to the minus
2 a good reference point.

00:25:46.970 --> 00:25:48.780 align:middle line:84%
And it's not necessarily
equal to that.

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:50.238 align:middle line:84%
It's greater than
or equal to that.

00:25:50.238 --> 00:25:52.950 align:middle line:84%
And the reason is our edges
may not be distributed evenly.

00:25:52.950 --> 00:25:56.760 align:middle line:84%
So if some vertices have
way more edges than others,

00:25:56.760 --> 00:25:59.290 align:middle line:84%
that will cause the number of
paths of length 2 to go up.

00:25:59.290 --> 00:26:02.840 align:middle line:90%


00:26:02.840 --> 00:26:05.220 align:middle line:84%
And again, we can
take the average.

00:26:05.220 --> 00:26:08.870 align:middle line:84%
So if I were to take the
average over A1 and A2

00:26:08.870 --> 00:26:12.450 align:middle line:84%
of the number of
paths from a1 to a2,

00:26:12.450 --> 00:26:15.500 align:middle line:84%
that would be at least I
would divide by A squared.

00:26:15.500 --> 00:26:22.120 align:middle line:90%
So K to the minus 2 times B.

00:26:22.120 --> 00:26:27.170 align:middle line:84%
As an exercise you can keep
going to longer lengths.

00:26:27.170 --> 00:26:34.546 align:middle line:84%
So exercise is that P3 is
at least K to the minus 3

00:26:34.546 --> 00:26:37.780 align:middle line:84%
A squared B squared, A
squared B squared would

00:26:37.780 --> 00:26:40.700 align:middle line:84%
be the number of paths of
length 3 in the complete graph,

00:26:40.700 --> 00:26:43.300 align:middle line:84%
and at least K to the
minus 3, a fraction of them

00:26:43.300 --> 00:26:44.745 align:middle line:90%
are paths in our smaller graph.

00:26:44.745 --> 00:26:47.440 align:middle line:90%


00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:53.080 align:middle line:84%
And that means that if I
take the average on A and B

00:26:53.080 --> 00:26:57.610 align:middle line:84%
of the number of paths of length
3 from a to b, that's at least K

00:26:57.610 --> 00:27:08.560 align:middle line:84%
to the minus 3 times A times B.
So if I pick two random vertices

00:27:08.560 --> 00:27:11.550 align:middle line:84%
and I count the number of
paths of length 3, on average,

00:27:11.550 --> 00:27:14.280 align:middle line:90%
it's at least this big.

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:17.382 align:middle line:84%
Now let's compare
that to the key lemma.

00:27:17.382 --> 00:27:28.410 align:middle line:84%
The key Lemma says that I can
find some substantial subsets,

00:27:28.410 --> 00:27:32.420 align:middle line:84%
so that within these
substantial subsets,

00:27:32.420 --> 00:27:35.120 align:middle line:84%
the number of paths
of length 3 is always

00:27:35.120 --> 00:27:41.300 align:middle line:84%
K to the minus 100
size of A size of B.

00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:47.840 align:middle line:84%
So this number here is a
small fraction of the average.

00:27:47.840 --> 00:27:50.660 align:middle line:84%
I'm looking for pairs where
the number of paths of length 3

00:27:50.660 --> 00:27:53.130 align:middle line:84%
is at least a small
fraction of the average.

00:27:53.130 --> 00:27:56.780 align:middle line:90%


00:27:56.780 --> 00:27:58.520 align:middle line:84%
But the thing that
makes this tricky

00:27:58.520 --> 00:28:02.120 align:middle line:84%
is I don't want just like
some A's and B's or most

00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:04.670 align:middle line:84%
of the A's and B's to be
at least a small fraction

00:28:04.670 --> 00:28:05.310 align:middle line:90%
of the average.

00:28:05.310 --> 00:28:09.430 align:middle line:84%
I want actually, for every
A and B in our subset,

00:28:09.430 --> 00:28:12.670 align:middle line:84%
I want them to be at least
some fraction of the average.

00:28:12.670 --> 00:28:24.510 align:middle line:90%


00:28:24.510 --> 00:28:30.430 align:middle line:84%
So now we're eventually going
to go up to paths of length 3.

00:28:30.430 --> 00:28:32.460 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:28:32.460 --> 00:28:36.460 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: For this one, we don't
need them to be all of them?

00:28:36.460 --> 00:28:42.540 align:middle line:84%
If 80% of A cross B had a
lot of paths between them,

00:28:42.540 --> 00:28:46.380 align:middle line:84%
then could we still not
have this [INAUDIBLE] hold

00:28:46.380 --> 00:28:49.140 align:middle line:90%
for just like a worse bound?

00:28:49.140 --> 00:28:52.500 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Great, OK.

00:28:52.500 --> 00:28:59.830 align:middle line:84%
So the question is in
this Lemma as written,

00:28:59.830 --> 00:29:03.970 align:middle line:84%
we have assumed that for every
A and B in A prime and B prime,

00:29:03.970 --> 00:29:08.040 align:middle line:84%
we have a lot of paths, which
then matches the key lemma.

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:11.640 align:middle line:84%
But the question is, did we
really need that in this lemma?

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:15.890 align:middle line:84%
Or could we have relaxed
a little bit over here?

00:29:15.890 --> 00:29:20.720 align:middle line:84%
So suppose instead of this lemma
that we only had this for most

00:29:20.720 --> 00:29:21.490 align:middle line:90%
A's and B's.

00:29:21.490 --> 00:29:24.110 align:middle line:90%


00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:26.330 align:middle line:90%
So let's do a little experiment.

00:29:26.330 --> 00:29:28.906 align:middle line:84%
So in blue, I'll
put an experiment.

00:29:28.906 --> 00:29:35.120 align:middle line:90%


00:29:35.120 --> 00:29:37.940 align:middle line:84%
And the experiment is
that instead of this, I'm

00:29:37.940 --> 00:29:45.800 align:middle line:84%
going to say for 90% of
pairs, a prime, b prime

00:29:45.800 --> 00:29:49.280 align:middle line:90%
and A prime cross B prime.

00:29:49.280 --> 00:29:49.830 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:49.830 --> 00:29:51.288 align:middle line:84%
So now let's see
what would happen.

00:29:51.288 --> 00:30:13.530 align:middle line:90%


00:30:13.530 --> 00:30:21.510 align:middle line:84%
If I take an element of this
sum before I knew that--

00:30:21.510 --> 00:30:26.705 align:middle line:84%
so let's say a prime plus
b prime is in this sum.

00:30:26.705 --> 00:30:30.540 align:middle line:90%


00:30:30.540 --> 00:30:34.910 align:middle line:84%
And then I can say that then
I'm going to use this thing.

00:30:34.910 --> 00:30:40.950 align:middle line:90%


00:30:40.950 --> 00:30:47.910 align:middle line:84%
Now if I knew that 99%
of the guys in this sum

00:30:47.910 --> 00:30:51.930 align:middle line:84%
could be represented by a
good pair, a prime, b prime,

00:30:51.930 --> 00:30:54.270 align:middle line:90%
I would be happy.

00:30:54.270 --> 00:30:58.770 align:middle line:84%
But that's not what I have
written in my experiment.

00:30:58.770 --> 00:31:03.130 align:middle line:84%
So my anxiety is 90% of the a
primes and b primes are good.

00:31:03.130 --> 00:31:05.440 align:middle line:90%
They have lots of paths.

00:31:05.440 --> 00:31:06.980 align:middle line:90%
10% of them are bad.

00:31:06.980 --> 00:31:09.850 align:middle line:84%
But then I take the
sum set, and the 90%

00:31:09.850 --> 00:31:13.972 align:middle line:84%
produce a few sums, but the
10% produce a ton of sums.

00:31:13.972 --> 00:31:14.805 align:middle line:90%
I'll make a picture.

00:31:14.805 --> 00:31:18.040 align:middle line:90%


00:31:18.040 --> 00:31:22.660 align:middle line:84%
So here is A prime
cross B prime.

00:31:22.660 --> 00:31:25.300 align:middle line:90%
This part of it is good.

00:31:25.300 --> 00:31:29.650 align:middle line:90%
Good means that.

00:31:29.650 --> 00:31:33.490 align:middle line:90%
And here's the 10% That's bad.

00:31:33.490 --> 00:31:35.936 align:middle line:90%
Then I take the sum operation.

00:31:35.936 --> 00:31:39.640 align:middle line:90%


00:31:39.640 --> 00:31:41.530 align:middle line:90%
But now life changes.

00:31:41.530 --> 00:31:43.485 align:middle line:90%
So pi 1 of good is tiny.

00:31:43.485 --> 00:31:48.850 align:middle line:90%


00:31:48.850 --> 00:31:51.015 align:middle line:90%
Pi one of bad is huge.

00:31:51.015 --> 00:31:57.670 align:middle line:90%


00:31:57.670 --> 00:31:58.990 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:01.750 align:middle line:90%
And now I go down here.

00:32:01.750 --> 00:32:06.880 align:middle line:84%
And for each of these
sums, if the sums are good,

00:32:06.880 --> 00:32:08.980 align:middle line:90%
they get counted many times.

00:32:08.980 --> 00:32:11.190 align:middle line:90%
If sums are bad, they don't.

00:32:11.190 --> 00:32:15.750 align:middle line:84%
But this isn't going
to work if pi 1 is bad.

00:32:15.750 --> 00:32:20.070 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: At this point, if
instead of assuming for 90%

00:32:20.070 --> 00:32:21.780 align:middle line:84%
if we assume that
the average is bigger

00:32:21.780 --> 00:32:29.550 align:middle line:84%
than p, then at this step, if
we added together every p in AB,

00:32:29.550 --> 00:32:32.160 align:middle line:90%
then would we get the same?

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:35.490 align:middle line:84%
Will the sum of the three
AB over each AB would

00:32:35.490 --> 00:32:38.670 align:middle line:84%
be less than the guys
in pi 1 of X cubed,

00:32:38.670 --> 00:32:42.297 align:middle line:84%
and then the sum of them will be
the number of times the average?

00:32:42.297 --> 00:32:44.380 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah so
there's another suggestion,

00:32:44.380 --> 00:32:46.410 align:middle line:90%
but I think it's similar.

00:32:46.410 --> 00:32:48.700 align:middle line:84%
The other suggestion
was instead of a 90%

00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:51.250 align:middle line:84%
we could take the average
over a prime b prime.

00:32:51.250 --> 00:32:52.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:32:52.830 --> 00:32:57.030 align:middle line:84%
But the issue is that when we
look sometimes at A prime cross

00:32:57.030 --> 00:33:01.060 align:middle line:84%
B prime and sometimes we
look at a prime plus b prime

00:33:01.060 --> 00:33:06.520 align:middle line:84%
and their notions of average
may be very different

00:33:06.520 --> 00:33:08.470 align:middle line:84%
from each other,
because there may

00:33:08.470 --> 00:33:11.080 align:middle line:84%
be a big chunk of A prime
cross B prime, which

00:33:11.080 --> 00:33:13.070 align:middle line:84%
is compressed a
lot when you add,

00:33:13.070 --> 00:33:14.970 align:middle line:90%
and another chunk which is not.

00:33:14.970 --> 00:33:21.670 align:middle line:90%


00:33:21.670 --> 00:33:24.260 align:middle line:84%
So when you look at
a prime plus b prime,

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:27.800 align:middle line:84%
we don't need every sum to
have a lot of representatives.

00:33:27.800 --> 00:33:29.770 align:middle line:90%
We just need most of them.

00:33:29.770 --> 00:33:33.400 align:middle line:84%
But it's hard to keep track of
the way A prime cross B prime is

00:33:33.400 --> 00:33:36.130 align:middle line:84%
related to a prime
plus b prime, and it

00:33:36.130 --> 00:33:37.690 align:middle line:84%
seems to be the case
that the easiest

00:33:37.690 --> 00:33:41.230 align:middle line:84%
way to know that most
of the sums are good

00:33:41.230 --> 00:33:44.400 align:middle line:84%
is to actually know that all of
A prime cross B prime is good.

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:47.170 align:middle line:90%


00:33:47.170 --> 00:33:47.740 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:33:47.740 --> 00:33:48.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:48.350 --> 00:33:49.190 align:middle line:90%
Great questions.

00:33:49.190 --> 00:33:50.022 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:33:50.022 --> 00:33:51.730 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Could you
get around this issue

00:33:51.730 --> 00:33:56.090 align:middle line:84%
by requiring that the bad
subset is asymptotically small,

00:33:56.090 --> 00:34:00.270 align:middle line:84%
that the size is 1 over the
square root of the size of A?

00:34:00.270 --> 00:34:04.930 align:middle line:84%
Because that way when you
project down, you'll square it,

00:34:04.930 --> 00:34:08.489 align:middle line:84%
but it will still
be relatively small.

00:34:08.489 --> 00:34:09.480 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Right.

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:13.830 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the comment
was that if we

00:34:13.830 --> 00:34:16.960 align:middle line:84%
were to replace 90%
by 1 minus epsilon,

00:34:16.960 --> 00:34:19.659 align:middle line:84%
and if we tuned epsilon to
be really, really small,

00:34:19.659 --> 00:34:21.840 align:middle line:90%
eventually this would work.

00:34:21.840 --> 00:34:25.260 align:middle line:90%
And that sounds right to me.

00:34:25.260 --> 00:34:27.699 align:middle line:84%
We'll keep our eye out
for the rest of the proof.

00:34:27.699 --> 00:34:30.960 align:middle line:84%
Perhaps, that will allow
us to simplify things.

00:34:30.960 --> 00:34:32.330 align:middle line:90%
But it might not.

00:34:32.330 --> 00:34:35.580 align:middle line:90%


00:34:35.580 --> 00:34:36.840 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:34:36.840 --> 00:34:39.880 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

00:34:39.880 --> 00:34:41.380 align:middle line:90%
So let's remember where we are.

00:34:41.380 --> 00:34:43.320 align:middle line:84%
We're trying to
prove the key lemma

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:47.370 align:middle line:84%
that I can choose big subsets,
so that for every pair a and b,

00:34:47.370 --> 00:34:49.989 align:middle line:84%
there are lots of length
3 paths between them.

00:34:49.989 --> 00:34:53.409 align:middle line:84%
And for every, maybe we
could relax to almost every,

00:34:53.409 --> 00:34:55.630 align:middle line:90%
but anyway, it's not that hard.

00:34:55.630 --> 00:34:59.440 align:middle line:84%
It's actually not that hard
to prove these theorems.

00:34:59.440 --> 00:34:59.990 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:59.990 --> 00:35:04.870 align:middle line:84%
So the reason we use 3
here is that, well, I

00:35:04.870 --> 00:35:08.080 align:middle line:84%
think that this is false with
2, if we replaced it with 2.

00:35:08.080 --> 00:35:10.270 align:middle line:84%
I don't quite have
a counterexample.

00:35:10.270 --> 00:35:13.323 align:middle line:90%


00:35:13.323 --> 00:35:15.125 align:middle line:84%
Buy still we're going
to warm up by talking

00:35:15.125 --> 00:35:16.750 align:middle line:84%
about paths of length
2 because they're

00:35:16.750 --> 00:35:18.260 align:middle line:90%
simpler than paths of length 3.

00:35:18.260 --> 00:35:21.267 align:middle line:84%
And we'll prove some weaker
version for paths of length 2

00:35:21.267 --> 00:35:22.725 align:middle line:84%
that we'll use as
a stepping stone.

00:35:22.725 --> 00:35:55.670 align:middle line:90%


00:35:55.670 --> 00:36:16.880 align:middle line:84%
So paths of length 2, so lemma,
If X is a subset of A cross B

00:36:16.880 --> 00:36:25.040 align:middle line:84%
and it's pretty big, and we
have a parameter epsilon bigger

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:28.983 align:middle line:84%
than 0, Then I can
choose subsets.

00:36:28.983 --> 00:36:37.010 align:middle line:90%


00:36:37.010 --> 00:36:40.850 align:middle line:84%
It's actually just one
subset, just a subset A prime.

00:36:40.850 --> 00:36:57.730 align:middle line:84%
So that A prime is
pretty big and P2 of a1,

00:36:57.730 --> 00:37:04.990 align:middle line:84%
a2, is at least epsilon
K to the minus 2 times b.

00:37:04.990 --> 00:37:07.610 align:middle line:90%
Now, not for every pair a1, a2.

00:37:07.610 --> 00:37:09.520 align:middle line:84%
We're going to weaken
that a little bit,

00:37:09.520 --> 00:37:14.760 align:middle line:84%
but with an exceptional set of
only about an epsilon fraction.

00:37:14.760 --> 00:37:31.498 align:middle line:90%


00:37:31.498 --> 00:37:33.190 align:middle line:84%
So actually the
people who set this up

00:37:33.190 --> 00:37:35.710 align:middle line:84%
had the thought that was
similar to yours, which

00:37:35.710 --> 00:37:40.602 align:middle line:84%
is that let's allow an
epsilon fraction of bad pairs,

00:37:40.602 --> 00:37:42.310 align:middle line:84%
and we'll make that
a parameter, and then

00:37:42.310 --> 00:37:44.590 align:middle line:90%
we'll see what we can do.

00:37:44.590 --> 00:37:47.710 align:middle line:84%
And actually we put an epsilon
in two different places.

00:37:47.710 --> 00:37:55.220 align:middle line:84%
And so, all right, so
let's process this first.

00:37:55.220 --> 00:37:58.890 align:middle line:84%
Remember that the average
number of paths from a1 to a2.

00:37:58.890 --> 00:38:00.350 align:middle line:84%
If we average over
all the choices

00:38:00.350 --> 00:38:03.170 align:middle line:90%
a1 and a2 is at least this big.

00:38:03.170 --> 00:38:08.000 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to be at least an
epsilon fraction of the average.

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:11.660 align:middle line:84%
And that's going to be
true not all the time but

00:38:11.660 --> 00:38:16.100 align:middle line:84%
except for about an
epsilon fraction of pairs.

00:38:16.100 --> 00:38:19.190 align:middle line:90%
And A prime is a decent size it.

00:38:19.190 --> 00:38:27.920 align:middle line:90%


00:38:27.920 --> 00:38:28.530 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:38:28.530 --> 00:38:32.780 align:middle line:84%
So before we try to prove this,
let me ask a question to people.

00:38:32.780 --> 00:38:39.450 align:middle line:84%
So question, Can we just
take A prime to be all of A?

00:38:39.450 --> 00:38:45.200 align:middle line:90%


00:38:45.200 --> 00:38:48.170 align:middle line:84%
So then we would
just keep this part.

00:38:48.170 --> 00:38:52.390 align:middle line:84%
Is it plausible that
the number of paths

00:38:52.390 --> 00:38:56.370 align:middle line:84%
is at least an epsilon fraction
of the average most of the time?

00:38:56.370 --> 00:38:59.290 align:middle line:90%


00:38:59.290 --> 00:39:01.240 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't sound so crazy.

00:39:01.240 --> 00:39:03.135 align:middle line:84%
Is it possible that
that's always true?

00:39:03.135 --> 00:39:32.320 align:middle line:90%


00:39:32.320 --> 00:39:35.870 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so the question is, what's
the maximum that this could be?

00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:37.852 align:middle line:84%
The maximum it could
be is B because there

00:39:37.852 --> 00:39:39.310 align:middle line:84%
are paths that
start at a1, they'll

00:39:39.310 --> 00:39:40.840 align:middle line:90%
go across to somebody in b.

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:42.350 align:middle line:90%
They'll come back to a2.

00:39:42.350 --> 00:39:44.830 align:middle line:90%
So they're at most b.

00:39:44.830 --> 00:39:47.300 align:middle line:84%
So there's a decent
amount of range there.

00:39:47.300 --> 00:39:48.780 align:middle line:90%
And that is important.

00:39:48.780 --> 00:39:53.120 align:middle line:90%


00:39:53.120 --> 00:39:56.270 align:middle line:84%
Oh, the answer to
this question is no.

00:39:56.270 --> 00:39:58.590 align:middle line:90%
And here's an example.

00:39:58.590 --> 00:40:00.590 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, was there a comment?

00:40:00.590 --> 00:40:05.420 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: And then could you
maybe have two points in A

00:40:05.420 --> 00:40:08.790 align:middle line:84%
connect them by a
every point in B,

00:40:08.790 --> 00:40:14.060 align:middle line:84%
and then every other point
in a is not very connected?

00:40:14.060 --> 00:40:15.240 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah, OK.

00:40:15.240 --> 00:40:24.200 align:middle line:84%
So the suggestion was
I take two points in A

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:31.430 align:middle line:84%
and I connect them to
all the points in B.

00:40:31.430 --> 00:40:37.105 align:middle line:84%
And then the rest of them
are not very connected.

00:40:37.105 --> 00:40:38.970 align:middle line:84%
Now two of them
might not be enough,

00:40:38.970 --> 00:40:42.740 align:middle line:90%
but it will take a few of them.

00:40:42.740 --> 00:40:47.640 align:middle line:84%
Here is B. Here this A.
This is a small piece.

00:40:47.640 --> 00:40:51.520 align:middle line:84%
I guess this could
be a small part of A.

00:40:51.520 --> 00:40:56.220 align:middle line:84%
And then over here, there are no
edges going out of there at all,

00:40:56.220 --> 00:40:57.600 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:40:57.600 --> 00:40:59.440 align:middle line:84%
So how big would
this have to be?

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:03.450 align:middle line:84%
Well, we need a fraction 1 over
k of all the edges in our graph.

00:41:03.450 --> 00:41:05.940 align:middle line:84%
So this small part
of A would have

00:41:05.940 --> 00:41:10.050 align:middle line:84%
size 1 over k times all
of A. And now I have a 1

00:41:10.050 --> 00:41:13.300 align:middle line:84%
over k fraction
of all the edges.

00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:16.170 align:middle line:84%
So if I pick a1
and a2 in here, I

00:41:16.170 --> 00:41:18.240 align:middle line:84%
have a ton of
paths between them.

00:41:18.240 --> 00:41:21.160 align:middle line:84%
But if either one
of them is out here,

00:41:21.160 --> 00:41:23.220 align:middle line:90%
there are no paths between them.

00:41:23.220 --> 00:41:27.430 align:middle line:84%
And this set is actually
much bigger than that set.

00:41:27.430 --> 00:41:29.340 align:middle line:84%
So for almost all
the pairs in A,

00:41:29.340 --> 00:41:31.030 align:middle line:90%
there are no paths between them.

00:41:31.030 --> 00:41:34.110 align:middle line:90%
So this is a counterexample.

00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:35.565 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:41:35.565 --> 00:41:38.860 align:middle line:84%
And there's a second
counterexample.

00:41:38.860 --> 00:41:41.550 align:middle line:84%
So in this counterexample,
the suspicious feature

00:41:41.550 --> 00:41:46.210 align:middle line:84%
is that these vertices have way
fewer edges than those vertices.

00:41:46.210 --> 00:41:48.800 align:middle line:90%


00:41:48.800 --> 00:41:50.720 align:middle line:84%
Could I also make
a counter example

00:41:50.720 --> 00:41:55.970 align:middle line:84%
where every vertex on both
sides has the same degree?

00:41:55.970 --> 00:41:57.270 align:middle line:90%
Yes, you can.

00:41:57.270 --> 00:42:00.360 align:middle line:84%
And it works by
dividing into clumps.

00:42:00.360 --> 00:42:02.600 align:middle line:90%
So I have a first clump.

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:04.260 align:middle line:90%
I have all the edges in here.

00:42:04.260 --> 00:42:07.400 align:middle line:90%
And then I have a second clump.

00:42:07.400 --> 00:42:11.120 align:middle line:90%
And I have all the edges here.

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:12.300 align:middle line:90%
And so on.

00:42:12.300 --> 00:42:15.600 align:middle line:84%
So if you do this and you have
k clumps of the same size,

00:42:15.600 --> 00:42:18.830 align:middle line:84%
then you'll see you have about
1 over k of all the edges.

00:42:18.830 --> 00:42:22.400 align:middle line:84%
And then if you pick a1
and a2, if you pick them

00:42:22.400 --> 00:42:25.250 align:middle line:84%
in different clumps, then there
are no paths between them.

00:42:25.250 --> 00:42:28.550 align:middle line:84%
If you pick them in the same
clump, there are lots of paths.

00:42:28.550 --> 00:42:30.720 align:middle line:84%
So because of
these two examples,

00:42:30.720 --> 00:42:37.705 align:middle line:84%
we cannot just take A
prime to be A. All right.

00:42:37.705 --> 00:42:40.830 align:middle line:84%
So we have to understand,
we need to pick A prime.

00:42:40.830 --> 00:42:45.570 align:middle line:84%
And now let's think about how
are we going to pick A prime.

00:42:45.570 --> 00:42:50.130 align:middle line:84%
And in both these examples, the
way to find a plausible A prime

00:42:50.130 --> 00:42:55.590 align:middle line:84%
is to pick some b and then
look at its neighborhood.

00:42:55.590 --> 00:42:58.090 align:middle line:84%
So here I pick some b and
I look at its neighborhood.

00:42:58.090 --> 00:42:59.160 align:middle line:90%
That's the set.

00:42:59.160 --> 00:43:00.910 align:middle line:90%
So this should be A prime right?

00:43:00.910 --> 00:43:04.570 align:middle line:84%
And here I pick some b anywhere,
and I look at its neighborhood.

00:43:04.570 --> 00:43:06.515 align:middle line:84%
And this is a reasonable
choice for A prime.

00:43:06.515 --> 00:43:14.460 align:middle line:90%


00:43:14.460 --> 00:43:20.940 align:middle line:84%
So we will take A prime
to be the neighborhood

00:43:20.940 --> 00:43:22.690 align:middle line:90%
of b for some b.

00:43:22.690 --> 00:43:45.140 align:middle line:90%


00:43:45.140 --> 00:43:50.810 align:middle line:84%
So now, so let me
make a definition.

00:43:50.810 --> 00:43:56.930 align:middle line:84%
I'll say a pair a1, a2
is called epsilon bad

00:43:56.930 --> 00:44:01.640 align:middle line:84%
if the number of paths
from a1 to A2 of length 2

00:44:01.640 --> 00:44:03.505 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than our
threshold there.

00:44:03.505 --> 00:44:08.210 align:middle line:90%


00:44:08.210 --> 00:44:08.940 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:44:08.940 --> 00:44:10.820 align:middle line:84%
So the main thing we
have to think about

00:44:10.820 --> 00:44:14.240 align:middle line:84%
is I'm going to pick
different b's and look

00:44:14.240 --> 00:44:15.420 align:middle line:90%
at their neighborhoods.

00:44:15.420 --> 00:44:17.000 align:middle line:84%
And for each
neighborhood, I want

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:20.450 align:middle line:84%
to count how many
bad pairs there are.

00:44:20.450 --> 00:44:31.631 align:middle line:84%
So BP epsilon of B is the
number of pairs a1, a2

00:44:31.631 --> 00:44:35.810 align:middle line:84%
that are both in the
neighborhood of b, so that a1,

00:44:35.810 --> 00:44:37.285 align:middle line:90%
a2 is epsilon bad.

00:44:37.285 --> 00:44:42.710 align:middle line:90%


00:44:42.710 --> 00:44:43.210 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:44:43.210 --> 00:44:46.810 align:middle line:84%
So we'd like to know
about how big that is.

00:44:46.810 --> 00:44:50.850 align:middle line:84%
And the easiest thing to
compute is its expectation.

00:44:50.850 --> 00:44:58.080 align:middle line:84%
So lemma, the expectation over
B of the size of this thing

00:44:58.080 --> 00:44:59.620 align:middle line:90%
is not too crazy.

00:44:59.620 --> 00:45:01.220 align:middle line:90%
So let's see what that means.

00:45:01.220 --> 00:45:08.490 align:middle line:90%


00:45:08.490 --> 00:45:12.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is at most
epsilon fraction K

00:45:12.420 --> 00:45:15.510 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 2 A squared.

00:45:15.510 --> 00:45:16.180 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:45:16.180 --> 00:45:18.880 align:middle line:90%
So let's digest this.

00:45:18.880 --> 00:45:20.560 align:middle line:90%
So we'll prove, of course.

00:45:20.560 --> 00:45:23.220 align:middle line:84%
But let's digest
the right-hand side.

00:45:23.220 --> 00:45:25.530 align:middle line:84%
So these bad pairs,
they're sitting

00:45:25.530 --> 00:45:27.370 align:middle line:90%
in just the set of all pairs.

00:45:27.370 --> 00:45:30.180 align:middle line:84%
So for reference, we
should think about how big

00:45:30.180 --> 00:45:33.090 align:middle line:90%
is the set of all pairs.

00:45:33.090 --> 00:45:39.640 align:middle line:84%
So let's take the expected
value over b of just the size

00:45:39.640 --> 00:45:41.270 align:middle line:90%
of its neighborhood squared.

00:45:41.270 --> 00:45:45.100 align:middle line:84%
That's at least K to
the minus 2 A squared.

00:45:45.100 --> 00:45:48.160 align:middle line:84%
This has an easy proof
that we'll do in a second.

00:45:48.160 --> 00:45:48.740 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:45:48.740 --> 00:45:51.430 align:middle line:84%
So if you compare these,
you see that the fraction

00:45:51.430 --> 00:45:55.510 align:middle line:84%
of epsilon bad pairs is
at most a small fraction

00:45:55.510 --> 00:45:57.880 align:middle line:90%
of the total pairs.

00:45:57.880 --> 00:46:04.180 align:middle line:84%
Fraction of epsilon bad pairs
is at most epsilon, on average.

00:46:04.180 --> 00:46:05.090 align:middle line:90%
And that's good.

00:46:05.090 --> 00:46:06.583 align:middle line:84%
That's the thing
we want to prove.

00:46:06.583 --> 00:46:08.500 align:middle line:84%
We want to prove there's
only about an epsilon

00:46:08.500 --> 00:46:09.450 align:middle line:90%
fraction of bad pairs.

00:46:09.450 --> 00:46:15.130 align:middle line:90%


00:46:15.130 --> 00:46:19.610 align:middle line:84%
So let's call this
lemma P1 and lemma P2.

00:46:19.610 --> 00:46:21.230 align:middle line:90%
This one is real easy.

00:46:21.230 --> 00:46:23.180 align:middle line:90%
So I can keep it on this board.

00:46:23.180 --> 00:46:24.670 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll
prove lemma P1 which

00:46:24.670 --> 00:46:25.970 align:middle line:90%
is the most important thing.

00:46:25.970 --> 00:46:32.940 align:middle line:84%
So Lemma P2 proof, if I take
the sum on b of N of b squared.

00:46:32.940 --> 00:46:37.830 align:middle line:90%


00:46:37.830 --> 00:46:41.880 align:middle line:84%
When you see this, what
does it make you want to do?

00:46:41.880 --> 00:46:45.390 align:middle line:90%
Actually, we already did it.

00:46:45.390 --> 00:46:50.970 align:middle line:84%
So this is the sum on b N
of b quantity squared over

00:46:50.970 --> 00:46:58.830 align:middle line:84%
the size of B. That's at least
C inverse A B all squared over

00:46:58.830 --> 00:47:05.940 align:middle line:84%
the size of B. That's at least
k to the minus 2 a squared B.

00:47:05.940 --> 00:47:09.750 align:middle line:84%
And to turn the sum into
an average, we divide by B,

00:47:09.750 --> 00:47:12.102 align:middle line:90%
by the size of B [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:12.102 --> 00:47:15.900 align:middle line:90%


00:47:15.900 --> 00:47:18.960 align:middle line:84%
Actually we could say
an even simpler thing.

00:47:18.960 --> 00:47:22.530 align:middle line:84%
So what's the average
size of just N of B?

00:47:22.530 --> 00:47:24.330 align:middle line:84%
The average size of
N of B is exactly

00:47:24.330 --> 00:47:29.350 align:middle line:84%
K inverse times the size of
A. And so by Cauchy-Schwarz,

00:47:29.350 --> 00:47:37.910 align:middle line:84%
then if you square
it, it's at least

00:47:37.910 --> 00:47:40.540 align:middle line:84%
So the heart of the
matter for this lemma

00:47:40.540 --> 00:47:43.390 align:middle line:84%
is that the expected
number of bad pairs

00:47:43.390 --> 00:47:46.600 align:middle line:84%
is a lot less than the
expected number of total pairs.

00:47:46.600 --> 00:47:48.165 align:middle line:90%
So let's prove this lemma.

00:47:48.165 --> 00:48:16.270 align:middle line:90%


00:48:16.270 --> 00:48:17.240 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:48:17.240 --> 00:48:26.620 align:middle line:84%
So proof of Lemma
P1, so again, let's

00:48:26.620 --> 00:48:33.250 align:middle line:84%
think about the sum on B of
the size of BP epsilon of b.

00:48:33.250 --> 00:48:36.140 align:middle line:90%


00:48:36.140 --> 00:48:37.910 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:48:37.910 --> 00:48:43.550 align:middle line:84%
So this is a set
of pairs a1, a2,

00:48:43.550 --> 00:48:46.392 align:middle line:90%
so this is a number of things.

00:48:46.392 --> 00:48:47.850 align:middle line:84%
This is a double
counting argument.

00:48:47.850 --> 00:48:55.640 align:middle line:84%
It's a number of a1, a2, and
b, so that a few things hold.

00:48:55.640 --> 00:49:00.895 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, we have
this connection pattern.

00:49:00.895 --> 00:49:05.840 align:middle line:90%


00:49:05.840 --> 00:49:09.200 align:middle line:84%
And also a1 and
a2 are bad, which

00:49:09.200 --> 00:49:12.320 align:middle line:84%
means the number of
paths from a1 to a2

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:23.210 align:middle line:84%
is at most epsilon
k to the minus 2 B.

00:49:23.210 --> 00:49:23.760 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:49:23.760 --> 00:49:26.570 align:middle line:90%
So how should we count this?

00:49:26.570 --> 00:49:29.095 align:middle line:84%
Initially, we put
the B on the outside.

00:49:29.095 --> 00:49:30.970 align:middle line:84%
But to count this
quantity, it's a lot easier

00:49:30.970 --> 00:49:36.500 align:middle line:84%
to pick a1 and a2 first, because
then after we fix a1 and a2,

00:49:36.500 --> 00:49:38.690 align:middle line:84%
we're counting how many
b's we can put there.

00:49:38.690 --> 00:49:42.250 align:middle line:84%
And this hypothesis is just a
bound on the number of b's that

00:49:42.250 --> 00:49:45.160 align:middle line:90%
go there.

00:49:45.160 --> 00:49:48.430 align:middle line:90%
So this is less than A squared.

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:50.330 align:middle line:90%
Pick any a1 and a2.

00:49:50.330 --> 00:49:54.830 align:middle line:84%
And then if a1 and a2
obey this condition,

00:49:54.830 --> 00:50:08.860 align:middle line:84%
there are at most this many
choices for B. And that's it.

00:50:08.860 --> 00:50:10.690 align:middle line:84%
Now I should convert
this sum to an average

00:50:10.690 --> 00:50:15.190 align:middle line:84%
by dividing by B. Then what's
left is epsilon K to the minus 2

00:50:15.190 --> 00:50:15.980 align:middle line:90%
A squared.

00:50:15.980 --> 00:50:47.780 align:middle line:90%


00:50:47.780 --> 00:50:51.710 align:middle line:84%
So we are now almost
done proving this lemma

00:50:51.710 --> 00:50:53.370 align:middle line:90%
about paths of length 2.

00:50:53.370 --> 00:50:57.320 align:middle line:84%
And I can fit the rest
of it in the little space

00:50:57.320 --> 00:50:58.950 align:middle line:84%
under the statement
of the lemma.

00:50:58.950 --> 00:51:12.270 align:middle line:90%


00:51:12.270 --> 00:51:16.430 align:middle line:84%
So on average, N of b is
pretty big my lemma 2.

00:51:16.430 --> 00:51:22.010 align:middle line:84%
On average, N of b
is bigger than this.

00:51:22.010 --> 00:51:27.190 align:middle line:84%
So proof, A prime is going
to be N of n for some b.

00:51:27.190 --> 00:51:34.097 align:middle line:84%
And on average, this
true because of lemma P1.

00:51:34.097 --> 00:51:36.430 align:middle line:84%
So we just need to be a little
careful about how exactly

00:51:36.430 --> 00:51:39.010 align:middle line:90%
to combine these two things.

00:51:39.010 --> 00:51:45.190 align:middle line:84%
And the way to do it is to
look at the average value of N

00:51:45.190 --> 00:51:51.070 align:middle line:84%
of b squared minus 1
over 2 epsilon times

00:51:51.070 --> 00:51:53.340 align:middle line:90%
the number of bad pairs.

00:51:53.340 --> 00:52:02.320 align:middle line:90%


00:52:02.320 --> 00:52:05.720 align:middle line:84%
So why do we combine things by
taking a linear combination?

00:52:05.720 --> 00:52:07.300 align:middle line:90%
We do that because that's nice.

00:52:07.300 --> 00:52:08.950 align:middle line:84%
Because of linearity
of expectation,

00:52:08.950 --> 00:52:11.740 align:middle line:84%
I can compute this directly
from the two lemmas computing

00:52:11.740 --> 00:52:13.010 align:middle line:90%
these things individually.

00:52:13.010 --> 00:52:14.770 align:middle line:84%
So that's why we'd
want to add them.

00:52:14.770 --> 00:52:16.960 align:middle line:90%
And what do we get?

00:52:16.960 --> 00:52:19.750 align:middle line:84%
Well, just plugging in the
bounds from lemma P1 and lemma

00:52:19.750 --> 00:52:24.515 align:middle line:84%
P2, we get that this is at
least 1/2 half K to the minus 2

00:52:24.515 --> 00:52:25.270 align:middle line:90%
A squared.

00:52:25.270 --> 00:52:30.640 align:middle line:90%


00:52:30.640 --> 00:52:43.040 align:middle line:84%
So now I choose b so that
N of b squared minus 1

00:52:43.040 --> 00:52:47.990 align:middle line:84%
over 2 epsilon BP epsilon
of b is greater than

00:52:47.990 --> 00:52:51.350 align:middle line:90%
or equal to its mean.

00:52:51.350 --> 00:52:56.840 align:middle line:84%
And I set A prime
to be this N of b.

00:52:56.840 --> 00:52:57.360 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:52:57.360 --> 00:53:00.270 align:middle line:84%
And then I claim we can read off
the two things we care about.

00:53:00.270 --> 00:53:04.070 align:middle line:84%
The first thing we care about
is that N of b is pretty big.

00:53:04.070 --> 00:53:06.260 align:middle line:84%
So we can ignore
this negative thing.

00:53:06.260 --> 00:53:08.610 align:middle line:84%
N of b squared is
at least this big.

00:53:08.610 --> 00:53:10.700 align:middle line:84%
And so N of b is
at least around k

00:53:10.700 --> 00:53:15.410 align:middle line:84%
inverse A. That is
bullet point one.

00:53:15.410 --> 00:53:20.270 align:middle line:84%
And bullet point two is that
there are only a small fraction

00:53:20.270 --> 00:53:23.280 align:middle line:90%
of bad pairs a1, a2.

00:53:23.280 --> 00:53:27.300 align:middle line:84%
Well, for this thing
is positive, so 1

00:53:27.300 --> 00:53:29.700 align:middle line:90%
over this one I'll write down.

00:53:29.700 --> 00:53:34.230 align:middle line:84%
So we get the
number of bad pairs

00:53:34.230 --> 00:53:36.000 align:middle line:84%
is at most-- bring
this over here

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:40.960 align:middle line:84%
and multiply, 2 epsilon times
the number of total pairs.

00:53:40.960 --> 00:53:44.200 align:middle line:84%
Only a 2 epsilon fraction
of the total pairs are bad.

00:53:44.200 --> 00:53:45.520 align:middle line:90%
That's this statement.

00:53:45.520 --> 00:53:58.710 align:middle line:90%


00:53:58.710 --> 00:54:02.060 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
about this lemma?

00:54:02.060 --> 00:54:04.830 align:middle line:90%


00:54:04.830 --> 00:54:08.940 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So at the
end, all the A's

00:54:08.940 --> 00:54:12.423 align:middle line:84%
